Outbreak of _E. coli_ infections
--------------------------------
As of 8 Apr 2019, 96 people infected with the outbreak strain of _E. coli_ O103 have been reported from 5 states. CDC is reporting the 96 illnesses that the PulseNet laboratory network has confirmed are part of this outbreak. States are investigating additional illnesses that might be a part of this outbreak.

State / Ill people
Georgia / 17
Kentucky / 46
Ohio / 5
Tennessee / 26
Virginia / 2
Total / 96

Illnesses started on dates from 2 to 26 Mar 2019. Ill people range in age from 1 to 81 years, with a median age of 17. 51 percent are female. Of 67 people with information available, 11 (16%) have been hospitalized. No deaths and no cases of hemolytic uremic syndrome have been reported.

This investigation is still ongoing and a specific food item, grocery store, or restaurant chain has not been identified as the source of infections. State and local public health officials are interviewing ill people to determine what they ate and other exposures in the week before their illness started. Federal and state regulatory officials use that information to guide efforts to identify a contaminated food and trace it to its source. Learn more about how public health and regulatory agencies investigate a foodborne disease outbreak at https://www.cdc.gov/foodsafety/outbreaks/investigating-outbreaks/investigations/index.html

CDC will provide more information as it becomes available.

